  <main id="full" class="relative mx-auto max-w-6xl px-4 py-16 space-y-24">

    <!-- Section: Dataset / Problem -->
    <section id="dataset" class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-10 items-center">
      <div class="md:col-span-5 reveal">
        <div class="relative aspect-[4/3] rounded-3xl overflow-hidden shadow-soft">
          <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-[url('https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1452570053594-1b985d6ea890?q=80&w=1400&auto=format&fit=crop')] bg-cover bg-center"></div>
          <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-tr from-charcoal/60 via-teal-900/30 to-transparent"></div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="md:col-span-7 reveal">
        <h2 class="hfont text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold">Dataset — A Small but Complete Sandbox</h2>
        <p class="mt-4 text-white/85 leading-relaxed">
          The Iris dataset is tiny by modern standards, but it’s perfect for testing out end-to-end ML habits.
          We have 150 labeled flowers, 4 numeric features (sepal &amp; petal measurements), and 3 species:
          <span class="text-teal-200 font-medium">setosa</span>, <span class="text-teal-200 font-medium">versicolor</span>, and
          <span class="text-teal-200 font-medium">virginica</span>. The goal: build a clear, reproducible pipeline that
          favors <em>interpretability</em> over leaderboard chasing.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-3 text-white/80 leading-relaxed">
          In this project, I treat Iris like a miniature production problem: clear splits, feature scaling where needed,
          simple baselines, and visualization of decision boundaries rather than just reporting a single accuracy number.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section: Framework -->
    <section id="framework" class="reveal">
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-8 items-start">
        <div class="md:col-span-5">
          <h2 class="hfont text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold">Modeling Framework</h2>
          <p class="mt-3 text-white/85">
            The codebase walks through the full pipeline: loading, splitting, preprocessing, modeling, and evaluation.
            Each step is intentionally minimal, so the patterns can scale to larger datasets without changing the mental model.
          </p>
          <div class="mt-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-3 gap-3">
            <div class="card rounded-2xl p-4">
              <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-white/60">Layer 1</p>
              <p class="hfont text-lg font-semibold text-teal-200">Data Prep</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-white/80 mt-1">Train / test split · feature scaling · label encoding</p>
            </div>
            <div class="card rounded-2xl p-4">
              <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-white/60">Layer 2</p>
              <p class="hfont text-lg font-semibold text-teal-200">Models</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-white/80 mt-1">Logistic Regression · Random Forest · SVM</p>
            </div>
            <div class="card rounded-2xl p-4">
              <p class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-white/60">Layer 3</p>
              <p class="hfont text-lg font-semibold text-teal-200">Insights</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-white/80 mt-1">Confusion matrices · decision regions · feature importance</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="md:col-span-7">
          <div class="rounded-3xl frost shadow-soft p-6">
            <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
              <div class="rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-600/40 to-teal-900/20 p-5 border border-white/10">
                <h3 class="hfont font-semibold text-teal-100">Train / Test Discipline</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-white/85 mt-2">
                  Models use a held-out test split and stratified cross-validation. Even on Iris, the habit of
                  separating tuning from evaluation matters more than the final percent or two.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-600/40 to-teal-900/20 p-5 border border-white/10">
                <h3 class="hfont font-semibold text-teal-100">Model Baselines</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-white/85 mt-2">
                  Start with multinomial logistic regression, then layer in tree-based models and SVM. Each model has
                  a clear role: baselines vs. non-linear boundaries vs. robustness.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-600/40 to-teal-900/20 p-5 border border-white/10">
                <h3 class="hfont font-semibold text-teal-100">Explainability</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-white/85 mt-2">
                  Decision regions and feature importance plots make it obvious which measurements separate species —
                  moving the project from “black box” to “teachable story”.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-600/40 to-teal-900/20 p-5 border border-white/10">
                <h3 class="hfont font-semibold text-teal-100">Reusable Patterns</h3>
                <p class="text-sm text-white/85 mt-2">
                  The same structure can be lifted into larger work: replace Iris with your own dataset, keep the
                  split / fit / evaluate loop intact, and extend metrics as needed.
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div class="mt-6 p-4 text-sm text-white/90 rounded-xl bg-charcoal/60 border border-white/10 italic">
              “If I can’t explain why the model chose a class on a tiny dataset, I won’t trust it later on a big one.”
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section: Results -->
    <section id="results" class="reveal">
      <h2 class="hfont text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold">Results — Beyond a Single Accuracy Number</h2>
      <p class="mt-3 text-white/80 max-w-3xl">
        Performance on Iris is famously “good”. The real point of this repo is to separate healthy evaluation from
        leaderboard screenshots, and to build intuition about where models disagree.
      </p>
      <div class="mt-6 grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
        <div class="rounded-3xl frost p-6 shadow-soft text-center">
          <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-white/70">Test accuracy (best model)</p>
          <p class="hfont text-4xl font-bold text-teal-200 mt-2">≈ 96%</p>
          <p class="text-white/70 text-sm mt-1">On held-out test split</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-3xl frost p-6 shadow-soft text-center">
          <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-white/70">Macro F1 score</p>
          <p class="hfont text-4xl font-bold text-teal-200 mt-2">≈ 0.96</p>
          <p class="text-white/70 text-sm mt-1">Balanced across all three classes</p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-3xl frost p-6 shadow-soft text-center">
          <p class="text-sm uppercase tracking-wider text-white/70">Misclassifications</p>
          <p class="hfont text-4xl font-bold text-teal-200 mt-2">Mostly 2↔3</p>
          <p class="text-white/70 text-sm mt-1">Versicolor vs. Virginica boundary, as expected</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section: Learnings / Engineering Habits -->
    <section id="learnings" class="reveal">
      <div class="rounded-3xl bg-gradient-to-br from-charcoal to-teal-900/30 border border-white/10 p-8 shadow-soft">
        <blockquote class="hfont text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold text-off/95 text-center">
          “Small datasets are where you practice the habits you need for big ones.”
        </blockquote>
        <div class="mt-8 grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
          <div class="card rounded-2xl p-5">
            <p class="hfont font-semibold text-teal-100">Modeling Habits</p>
            <p class="text-white/85 text-sm mt-1">
              Start simple, document assumptions, and log configuration. Treat every run as if someone else will
              reproduce it six months from now.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card rounded-2xl p-5">
            <p class="hfont font-semibold text-teal-100">Experiment Discipline</p>
            <p class="text-white/85 text-sm mt-1">
              Separate tuning from evaluation, even when it feels like overkill. Iris is a sandbox for
              learning why that matters.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="card rounded-2xl p-5">
            <p class="hfont font-semibold text-teal-100">Communication</p>
            <p class="text-white/85 text-sm mt-1">
              Visuals (decision regions, confusion matrices) make it easier to explain “what the model sees”
              to non-ML teammates.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Section: Looking Ahead -->
    <section id="future" class="reveal">
      <div class="relative overflow-hidden rounded-3xl p-10 border border-white/10 shadow-soft">
        <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-600/25 via-teal-900/20 to-charcoal"></div>
        <div class="relative">
          <h2 class="hfont text-2xl md:text-3xl font-semibold">Next Steps</h2>
          <p class="text-white/85 mt-3 max-w-3xl">
            The Iris project is intentionally small, but the patterns extend outward: swap in tabular production data,
            plug in more robust evaluation (ROC curves, calibration, drift checks), and wrap the pipeline in a simple
            API or dashboard. The goal is to have <em>one</em> mental template that scales from toy datasets to real
            ML products.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

